---
// Below-hero landing sections. Honesty is the centrepiece: the "protected" and
// "NOT protected" panels carry equal weight, because the product's standing bar is
// to never oversell.
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const protectedList = [
  ['Credentials', 'No ~/.ssh, ~/.npmrc, ~/.aws, or home dir reaches the container.'],
  ['Persistence', '.git, .github, .husky, .claude, … and package.json are read-only, so an install can’t plant auto-running hooks.'],
  ['Egress', 'Default-deny. The install reaches only the registry hosts you allow.'],
  ['Capabilities', '--cap-drop ALL, no-new-privileges, container-root ≠ host-root.'],
];
const notProtected = [
  ['Your source tree', 'Even in the container, package managers need a writable root, so a malicious dep can still edit src/ during install. Use --frozen for a read-only tree, and review git diff.'],
  ['Anything you grant', 'ssh-agent, paths, env, network. Grant the minimum; prefer ssh-agent over key files.'],
  ['A package not yet flagged', 'The gates catch known-bad versions. A malicious version no advisory has seen yet still installs. On the native path it runs on your host. In the explicit container path it runs against the box instead.'],
];
const workflows = [
  ['Vet a package before installing', 'check', 'A read-only review pass (no Docker): OSV advisories, typosquats, fresh/deprecated versions, all before a byte is fetched.', `${base}/vetting/`],
  ['Gate dependencies in CI', 'ci', 'verify the boundary is committed, delta to gate only a PR’s dependency changes, scan for newly-flagged malware, secrets for committed credentials.', `${base}/ci/`],
  ['Isolate a coding agent', 'agent', 'A PreToolUse hook that blocks bare npm/npx on the host, or a generated devcontainer that runs the whole session inside the jail.', `${base}/agent-isolation/`],
];
---

<section class="band">
  <h2 class="band__title">Start with sandbox add.</h2>
  <p class="band__lede">
    <code>sandbox add zod</code> and <code>sandbox install</code> are the everyday path. They auto-detect
    npm/pnpm/yarn/bun, run every target version through the supply-chain gates (release-age cooldown, OSV
    malware, risk hints) <em>before a byte is fetched</em>, then install mode-aware: native on a fresh or
    host-native project, contained when the tree already is container-built. Each write opens with one
    orient line that says what it will do and why. Your real <code>pnpm</code> is never shadowed.
  </p>
  <div class="works">
    {['sandbox add zod', 'sandbox install', 'sandbox check express', 'sandbox devcontainer init'].map((c) => (
      <code class="works__pill">{c}</code>
    ))}
  </div>
  <p class="band__lede" style="margin-top: var(--space-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);">
    Expert shortcut: the per-PM binaries are the same gated, mode-aware path with shorter keystrokes.
    <code>spnpm add zod</code> is <code>sandbox-pnpm add zod</code>. Use explicit <code>sandbox pnpm add zod</code>
    when you want the throwaway-container boundary.
  </p>
  <div class="works">
    {['sandbox-pnpm add zod', 'spnpm install', 'snpx vite', 'sandbox-npm ci'].map((c) => (
      <code class="works__pill">{c}</code>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<section class="band">
  <h2 class="band__title">Honest about what protects you</h2>
  <p class="band__lede">The whole sale is trust, so the line stays in plain sight. Every install vets the target versions first. The throwaway container is the real boundary when you ask for it with explicit sandbox package-manager syntax or a devcontainer. Here is exactly what that boundary covers and the one thing it does not.</p>
  <div class="panels">
    <div class="panel panel--yes">
      <p class="panel__head"><span class="panel__mark">✓</span> In the container (when you opt in)</p>
      <dl>
        {protectedList.map(([t, d]) => (<><dt>{t}</dt><dd>{d}</dd></>))}
      </dl>
    </div>
    <div class="panel panel--no">
      <p class="panel__head"><span class="panel__mark panel__mark--ochre">!</span> Not protected</p>
      <dl>
        {notProtected.map(([t, d]) => (<><dt>{t}</dt><dd>{d}</dd></>))}
      </dl>
      <p class="panel__foot">The gates catch known-bad packages and the container contains the rest. We’d rather say where the line is than imply there isn’t one.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="band">
  <h2 class="band__title">Security that stays out of the way</h2>
  <p class="band__lede">A clean install barely says anything. A finding is specific and tells you exactly what to do. Real output:</p>
  <div class="shots">
    <pre class="shot"><code><span class="c-dim">$ sandbox add zod</span>
<span class="c-ok">✓ gates passed, installing natively</span>
<span class="c-ok">  on the host</span></code></pre>
    <pre class="shot"><code><span class="c-ochre">sandbox: 1 thing worth a look before installing</span>
<span class="c-ochre">  left-pad@99.0.0</span>
<span class="c-dim">  !! very recently published 2 hours ago</span>
<span class="c-dim">heads-up only. Continuing. Use explicit sandbox</span>
<span class="c-dim">pnpm add left-pad for the throwaway container.</span></code></pre>
    <pre class="shot"><code><span class="c-dim">$ sandbox pnpm add zod</span>
<span class="c-dim">sandbox blocked 1 request to a host not on your</span>
<span class="c-dim">allowlist:</span>
<span class="c-ochre">  ⚠ telemetry.example.com, not a known registry</span>
<span class="c-dim">Allow once · save for the team · cancel?</span></code></pre>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="band">
  <h2 class="band__title">Three ways to use it</h2>
  <ul class="flows">
    {workflows.map(([title, tag, body, href]) => (
      <li class="flow">
        <a href={href} class="flow__link">
          <span class="flow__tag">{tag}</span>
          <span class="flow__title">{title}</span>
          <span class="flow__body">{body}</span>
        </a>
      </li>
    ))}
  </ul>
</section>

<style>
  .band { max-width: 64rem; margin-inline: auto; padding-block: clamp(2.5rem, 1.5rem + 4vw, 4rem); border-top: 1px solid var(--sbx-border); }
  .band__title { font-family: var(--sbx-font-display); font-weight: 640; font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 1.1rem + 1.6vw, 2rem); letter-spacing: -0.025em; color: var(--sl-color-white); margin: 0; }
  .band__lede { max-width: 60ch; color: var(--sl-color-gray-2); margin: var(--space-lg) 0 var(--space-2xl); }

  .works { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: var(--space-md); }
  .works__pill { font-family: var(--sl-font-mono); font-size: 0.86rem; color: var(--sl-color-gray-1); background: var(--sbx-surface); border: 1px solid var(--sbx-border); border-radius: 0.5rem; padding: 0.45rem 0.7rem; }
  .works__pill span { color: var(--sbx-accent); }

  .panels { display: grid; gap: var(--space-xl); grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  @media (min-width: 48rem) { .panels { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } }
  /* Starlight's splash body adds a top margin to consecutive siblings (.sl-markdown-content * + *).
     These grids space via `gap`, so that inherited margin only offsets the 2nd+ item (it pushed the
     "Not protected" panel below "In the container"). This component owns its spacing, so zero it out. */
  .panels > *, .shots > *, .flows > * { margin-top: 0; }
  .panel { border: 1px solid var(--sbx-border); border-radius: var(--sbx-radius); padding: var(--space-2xl); background: var(--sbx-surface); }
  .panel--no { background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--sbx-ochre) 7%, var(--sl-color-bg)); border-color: color-mix(in oklch, var(--sbx-ochre) 30%, var(--sbx-border)); }
  .panel__head { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.6ch; font-weight: 700; font-size: 1.05rem; margin: 0 0 var(--space-lg); color: var(--sl-color-white); font-family: var(--sbx-font-display); }
  .panel__mark { display: inline-grid; place-items: center; width: 1.4rem; height: 1.4rem; border-radius: 50%; font-size: 0.8rem; background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--sbx-accent) 22%, transparent); color: var(--sbx-accent-bright); }
  .panel__mark--ochre { background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--sbx-ochre) 22%, transparent); color: var(--sbx-ochre); }
  .panel dl { margin: 0; display: grid; gap: var(--space-md); }
  .panel dt { font-weight: 600; color: var(--sl-color-white); }
  .panel dd { margin: 0 0 var(--space-sm); color: var(--sl-color-gray-2); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.55; }
  .panel__foot { margin: var(--space-lg) 0 0; font-size: 0.86rem; color: var(--sbx-ochre); }

  .shots { display: grid; gap: var(--space-lg); grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  @media (min-width: 52rem) { .shots { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); } }
  .shot { margin: 0; background: var(--sbx-term-bg); border: 1px solid var(--sbx-border); border-radius: var(--sbx-radius); padding: var(--space-lg); font-family: var(--sl-font-mono); font-size: 0.76rem; line-height: 1.65; overflow-x: auto; }
  .shot code { background: none; border: 0; padding: 0; color: var(--sbx-term-fg); white-space: pre; }
  .c-dim { color: color-mix(in oklch, var(--sbx-term-fg) 62%, transparent); }
  .c-ok { color: var(--sbx-accent-bright); }
  .c-ochre { color: var(--sbx-ochre); }

  .flows { list-style: none; margin: 0; padding: 0; display: grid; gap: var(--space-md); }
  .flow__link { display: grid; gap: var(--space-xs); padding: var(--space-xl); border: 1px solid var(--sbx-border); border-radius: var(--sbx-radius); background: var(--sbx-surface); text-decoration: none; transition: border-color 150ms, transform 150ms cubic-bezier(0.2,0.8,0.2,1); }
  .flow__link:hover { border-color: var(--sbx-accent); transform: translateY(-1px); }
  .flow__tag { font-family: var(--sl-font-mono); font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--sbx-accent); letter-spacing: 0.03em; }
  .flow__title { font-weight: 640; font-size: 1.05rem; color: var(--sl-color-white); font-family: var(--sbx-font-display); }
  .flow__body { color: var(--sl-color-gray-2); font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.55; }
</style>
